[Event "Caro-Kann Defense: Main Variations"]
[Result "*"]

{The Caro-Kann is one of the most reliable defenses to 1.e4. Black gets a solid pawn structure and avoids the bad bishop problem of the French Defense.} 1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann. Black prepares ...d5 while keeping the light-squared bishop unblocked.} 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 {The main line.} (3. e5 {The Advance Variation.} Bf5 {Developing the bishop outside the pawn chain — the key advantage over the French.} 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 {Attacking the base of the chain, just like in the French but with the bishop already active.} 6. Be3 Nc6 7. O-O Nge7 {A flexible setup. Black will play ...Be7 and ...O-O.} (7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9. Bxd4 Ne7 {Heading for f5 or d5.})) (3. exd5 {The Exchange Variation.} cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qd7 {Solid equality for Black.}) (3. f3 {The Fantasy Variation — aggressive and sharp.} dxe4 4. fxe4 e5 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. Bc4 {White has an open position but weak squares.}) dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 {The Classical Caro-Kann — the most popular line.} (4... Nd7 {The Modern/Karpov Variation.} 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 {The aggressive approach.} Ngf6 6. Ng5 e6 7. Qe2 Nb6 {A sharp position.}) Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Nf3 Bg4 {A solid, slightly passive but very resilient position for Black.}) 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 {The main line. White expands on the kingside, trying to trade off Black's bishop.} h6 7. Nf3 Nd7 8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 {Black has a rock-solid position. The light squares are well controlled and the pawn structure is healthy.} 11. Bf4 (11. Bd2 {A quieter approach.} Ngf6 12. O-O-O Be7 {Both sides have clear plans.}) Ngf6 12. O-O-O Be7 13. Kb1 O-O {A typical Classical Caro-Kann middlegame. White has space on the kingside; Black is solid everywhere.} *
